<br>
BTW, the modifier does not affet the skill increase, just the chance of successfully crafting. <br>
<br>
It is when you approach the 200 limit that the 5% will really make a difference, as the success-probability gaps beyond 200.<br>
<br>
So for high-end items (as an example the Fine Velious Furs) at a trivial ranking let's say at 250, your chance of making the item boosts up when you reach 200. That means your REAL skill level + 5% modifier become useful if the total &gt;200.<br>
<br>
Sorry if my explanation seems a bit unclear, let's take an example.<br>
<br>
Let's say you want to make a Othmir Fur Hat (he he why especially THAT example, my tailor fellows will /rofl) which becomes trivial over 250.<br>
<br>
Till 199, your success rate will be very bad. At 200, it starts to become better (the formula seems not to be linear).<br>
<br>
So if your real skill is at 158, and you have the focus item, you will be considered as having a skill of 158 + 0.05*158 = 165.9 (say 166).<br>
<br>
But the increase of success rate between 158 and 166 is neglectable as you are still far below the 200 mark.<br>
<br>
Now if your skill is at 191, with the focus item, you are considered as having a skill of 191 + 191*0.05 = 200.55 (say 201). THAT is useful as you just crossed the mythical Grand Master Borderline ...<br>
<br>
In summary REAL SKILL + %BONUS &gt; 200 is useful for high-end items, &lt;200 neglectable.<br>
<br>
So same logic applies to the higher focus items (there is a dropped cloak which gives 15%), just keep in mind following formula :<br>
<br>
(Trade Skill Level) * 1.b &gt; 200 where &quot;b&quot; is the value in % of the bonus.<br>
<br>
